{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529662"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:56:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:56:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14439"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14439"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.03,0.07,0.61,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7134"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81778"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7134"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14439"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67069"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1027"},{"type":"tags","id":"4845"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17038"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27504"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35072"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43526"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81778"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her daughter, who is concerned about her mother\u0027s memory problems over the past three months. The patient reports difficulty concentrating and remembering recent events. She has a history of major depressive disorder but no other significant medical history. She takes sertraline 50 mg daily. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She is oriented to person and place but not to time. During cognitive testing, she frequently says \u0022I don\u0027t know\u0022 and appears distressed by her inability to answer questions. Her daughter mentions that her mother\u0027s performance seems to fluctuate, with some days being better than others.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Frontotemporal dementia","Vascular dementia","Lewy body dementia","Pseudodementia","Alzheimer\u0027s disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Epseudodementia\u003C/strong\u003E. Pseudodementia is a syndrome of cognitive impairment that mimics dementia but is actually caused by depression. Several features in this case point towards pseudodementia rather than a true dementia:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1. Relatively rapid onset (three months) of cognitive symptoms\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2. History of major depressive disorder\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E3. Inconsistent cognitive deficits (daughter reports fluctuating performance)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E4. Distress at inability to answer questions, suggesting preserved insight\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E5. Frequent \u0022I don\u0027t know\u0022 responses, which are more common in pseudodementia than true dementia\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlzheimer\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically has a more gradual onset over years rather than months. Patients with Alzheimer\u0027s disease often try to hide their deficits and may confabulate rather than admitting they don\u0027t know an answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVascular dementia\u003C/strong\u003E usually has a stepwise progression and is associated with cardiovascular risk factors, which are not mentioned in this case. The cognitive deficits in vascular dementia are typically more stable than the fluctuating course described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELewy body dementia\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by fluctuating cognition, but also typically includes visual hallucinations and parkinsonian features, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrontotemporal dementia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with personality changes, disinhibition, or language deficits rather than memory problems as the primary symptom. It also tends to have an earlier onset, usually before age 65.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to managing pseudodementia lies in recognizing it and addressing the underlying depression. In most cases, cognitive symptoms improve significantly with adequate treatment of depression. However, while pseudodementia is a strong consideration, it is essential to conduct a thorough workup to rule out other potential causes of cognitive impairment. This workup may include neuropsychological testing to assess the pattern and severity of cognitive dysfunction and neuroimaging, such as MRI or CT, to exclude structural brain abnormalities or other organic causes of cognitive decline. Blood tests to assess for metabolic, endocrine, or nutritional deficiencies (e.g., vitamin B12, thyroid function) should also be considered as part of the diagnostic process.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pseudodementia is a syndrome of cognitive impairment that mimics dementia but is caused by depression.","Key features distinguishing pseudodementia from true dementia include a relatively rapid onset, inconsistent cognitive deficits, and preserved insight.","Treatment of the underlying depression often leads to improvement in cognitive symptoms in pseudodementia."],"references":["Brodaty H, Pond D. Diagnosis and management of dementia in general practice. Australian Family Physician. 2004 Oct;33(10)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67069"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14439"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67069"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T21:25:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T21:28:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7134"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81778"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rela